segments.text: Dr. Melcher says, Ms. Brown, it's really serious.
He says, you know, this could kill you.
I said, oh, Dr. Melcher, I don't think so.
I said, I'm not going to get excited and worry about this.
The law will take care of it.
And so he said, well, come on.
See, it was Saturday at noon then.
He said, come back early Monday morning.
So I came on home, studied my Sunday school lesson, went to Sunday school church, taught my Sunday school class, and acted just like I always did when he was scared.
But Monday morning, I went back there, and like he said, he says, I have not been able to sleep hard this weekend worrying about you.
And he said, I don't know what I'm going to do to get that poison out of your head.
He said, I'm going to x-ray it again right now and see if it's gone away.
And I said, all right, so he x-rayed it again, and it was still right there.
And he said, well, I tell you, the only thing I know to do to get rid of it is to cut your head open, operate on it.
I said, now, Dr. Melcher, I haven't been afraid until now, but I said, I'm scared to death now.
I'm not going to have my head cut open my hole.
So I said, you'll have to give me a few minutes, if you will, please, before I give you an answer about that.
I'll have to go home and pray about it.
I said, I have a Heavenly Father who works out my problems for me, and I said, I want to talk this over with Him and see what He says for me to do about it.
So I keep a Bible on my kitchen table,
And I came home and went to the kitchen table and sat down.
My husband was living in those days.
And I said, now, Father, you heard what Dr. Melcher had just said to me, and I want to ask you what I must do about it.
He wants to operate on my head and cut it open and get the poison out, and I do not know what in this world to do, so please tell me.
So I said, I'm going to again ask you to take my hands and tell me in the Bible what your answer is.
So I turned to the scripture, and it said, Daughter, thy faith hath made thee holy, going peaceful.
So I picked up my phone, and I first thanked the Lord.
I knew that I was healed.
I knew the poison was gone.
I picked up my telephone right there on the kitchen table by me, and I said, Dr. Melcher,
you don't need to worry about me anymore.
I said, God has just healed my head.
And he said, Ms. Brown, have you lost your mind?
I said, no, I haven't lost my mind.
I said, you know, I told you I was coming home to pray about it.
And so I said, I did.
And I said, God has just healed me.
He said, will you please get in your car and come back down here?
He said, I don't know what's the matter with you, but he said, I've got to examine your head again.
So I went right straight back.
I had been gone about 20 minutes.
He accelerated again, and the party was gone.
He said, Ms. Bryan, it is a miracle.
I said, well, of course it was.
I told you that.

Then one day, we were going to have a vacation Bible school at our church, and the telephone rang, and the man who was in charge of the Bible school at our church said, Ms. Bryan, I want to ask a big favor of you.
He said, we hope
elected a woman to be principal of our Bible school.
And he says, lo and behold, she's real sick.
She's been put to bed.
The doctor says she won't be well for maybe months.
And he said, we don't have the faculty for the Bible school, and we don't have the literature.
We don't have anything.
And he says, I'm sick in bed with a blood clot in my leg.
And he said, I just wonder if you would promise to be principal of Bible school.
And he says, you know, it's just a month until it starts.
Well, that is a tremendous job.
You have to get about 125 workers.
You have to honor the literature.
You have to have all kinds of meetings and tell those women and men what they have to do.
And you have a lot of advertising people.
It's just a tremendous job.
And I said, Mr. Griffin, I fell off my sideboard, that very one right over there yesterday.
I got up there to pull that blind down, and I fell off the sideboard.
And I said, I've got some broken ribs.
And I said, I'm just suffering terribly with broken ribs this morning.
He said, oh, isn't that just awful?
I said, well, now, wait a minute.
I said, Mr. Griffin, you know the Lord can heal my ribs if he needs me to be principal of Bible school.
So I said, let's pray about it.
So he said, well, we certainly will.
So I just told the Lord, I said, now, dear Heavenly Father, if you need me to be principal of that Bible school, I'll do it if you'll heal my ribs, but I'm not able with broken ribs.
So I had forgotten when it was two days of three.
The Lord healed my broken ribs.
And I went ahead.
I was principal of Bible school.
We got everything all ready on time.
We had a wonderful school.
Lost souls were saved.
The girls and boys found Christ.
I love them.
And I went on to be principal the next two years after that.
And then not so terribly long ago, my family had been here one night
just Christmas Eve for Christmas dinner.
And we had strawberry parsley for dessert with fruit cake.
And, of course, that was Christmas Eve night, so the next thing was Christmas, and I was here by myself because my husband was gone.
And I always let my son and his wife and their family have that veil for me to be with her family.
And so I was here all by myself, and I went in the kitchen and ate the leftovers
from Christmas dinner the night before, and I wound up with strawberry parfait.
And the strawberries had been nice, crushed, but they were still, you know, big.
They were still the normal size.
And so one of those went the wrong way and got down in my windpipe or something down in my chest.
I couldn't get it up, and I couldn't get it down, and I tried everywhere in this world.
I caught, and I gained, and I went on.
And that thing would not budge.
So it was getting along toward dark that afternoon.
I'd been playing around with that thing all afternoon, trying to do it myself.
And I would say every now and then, I'd say, well, Lord, please help me.
But I wasn't really praying.
You know, real prayer is different from the way we pray sometimes.
So it began to get dark.
And I thought, well, I just got to go to the hospital.
I was still here all by myself.
So I got on my car and I drove myself down to the Brown Hospital.
And there was an orderly and a nurse on duty.
Everybody else was at home for Christmas dinner that night.
Because that was Christmas Day.
And so I said, what am I going to do?
She said, there's not a doctor in the hospital.
But she said, I'll call one and ask him to come and do something to help you.
And I said, well, somebody's going to have to help me because I can't go to bed tonight.
I couldn't even lie down.
It was so uncomfortable.
And I hadn't been able to eat.
And so she called the doctor, and he wouldn't come.
He didn't want to leave his family for Christmas.
Then I couldn't blame him.
But anyway, he said, give her a shot and tell her to eat a piece of bread.
So I said, well, it's not going to be any good.
I can't eat bread.
I've been trying all afternoon to get something down.
I said, I can't swallow it.
And I said, I don't believe a shot was going to get in.
So she gave me the shot, and it hurt like fury.
And I got in my car and came on home, and it was just the same old thing.
I couldn't eat any bread at all.
So then it was getting along toward bedtime, and then I was going to really cry.
So I said, Father, you know that I had been trying all afternoon to get rid of that strawberry.
I said, I had been to the hospital.
I tried to get a doctor, and he wouldn't come.
And I said, I don't have any family.
My husband's dead and in heaven.
And my son is having Christmas with his wife and her family.
And I don't want to disturb them.
And I said, I have only you.
And I said, you are sufficient.
You're all I need.
So I said, I'm going to ask you now to really get rid of this strawberry for me.
So I went in the bathroom and gave myself again.
And up came the strawberry.
Oh.
Then another time, I was hurrying to go to my circle meeting, a church meeting, you know, for women, where we studied the Bible.
So I got all dressed and came downstairs, and my powder room is where I put my cosmetics on, my makeup.
So I stepped in my elevator.
I have an electric elevator.
So I stepped in that elevator and pushed the down button, and it wouldn't budge.
I mean, it got halfway down, and then it would not go any further.
It just was hanging between the two floors.
I tried to push the up button, it wouldn't go up.
When I pushed the down button, it wouldn't go down.
It just was hanging there between the first and second floor.
So I jumped up and down trying to make it fall.
And it was too far for me to jump.
So I thought, what am I going to do?
And my first thought was to panic.
And then I thought, well, I don't have to panic.
I have a Heavenly Father who can do all things.
So I just bowed my head and prayed, and I said, Father, you know now what a predicament I've gotten myself in again.
And I said, I do not have a soul in this world.
I said, my friends are not going to come here because they all know I go to the circle on Tuesday morning.
And my husband is dead.
My son's already been here this morning for his visit.
And I said, I haven't phoned for the plumber or the carpenter or anybody like that to come.
So I said, I'll probably hang here until tomorrow morning.
When my son comes back again, unless you help me, I said, now, Father, you are all in this world I need, so I'm putting myself in your hands.
I said, you know, I can't even make my neighbors hear.
I don't believe you.
I said, it's summertime.
They all shut up with the air conditioning going.
And I said, I just don't know what you can do about it.
Of course, so human, you know, I began trying to help God work it out.
So I said, I'll tell you what, I think my daughter-in-law is the nearest one to me.
So I said, of course, you could send her outdoors.
And I said, of course, I'm not going to know when she comes outdoors because there was draperies hanging all in the windows and everything.
But I said, Lord, you could tell me when she comes outdoors.
And then I just screamed at the top of my voice.
And I said, in the meantime, I'm just going to wait for you to tell me that she's come outdoors.
So I stood there, I don't know how many minutes, not over six or seven.
And all that time I was thinking, well, I know God's going to get somebody up here to help me.
So in a few minutes he said to me, you know, God talks to you through your feelings.
That's one way he talks to us.
And so he just put the feeling on me just so plainly that I should call.
He said to me, now call.
She's outdoors now.
So I just screamed normal at the top of my voice.
That's my husband.
son's wife's name.
So in just about two seconds, she was at my back door.
She said, Ruth, what is the matter with you?
She said, what's happened?
Are you sick or something?
I said, no.
Norma, I'm stuck in the elevator.
I said, please go in my garage.
There's a short ladder in there.
And will you please bring the ladder so I can climb down the elevator?
So she said, well, of course.
So she
I said, there's a key outdoors, and I told her where to get the key to unlock the door.
So she came in and brought the flapper, and I climbed down out of the elevator.
And I said, now, Mama, what were you doing a while ago before you heard me call you?
She said, well, you know, it's the strangest thing.
She said, I was in the house getting ready to shampoo my hair.
I had my towel and my shampoo in my hand, and she said, all of a sudden, it just came over me that I must go outdoors.
Oh.
So she said, I didn't know what in the world I was going outdoors for.
She said, I thought maybe something terrible was happening out there or something.
But she said, something said to me that I must go outdoors.
So she said, I went outdoors.
And instantly, I heard you call.
Oh.
So if anybody ever says to me that they do not believe in prayer, I pay no attention to them.
I try to tell them that they're wrong.
God certainly does hear and answer prayer.
And I don't know what this world I'd do without him.
So in a worldly sense, I've had a very uneventful life.
My life has been spent in spiritual ways, mainly.
Of course, it's important.
Which is the best kind of life in the world to have.
You know, this life is so short.
Now, you see, I'm almost 80 years old.
And of course, when you get to be 80, you don't expect to be around too much longer.
Well, you'd think that, oh, woman, I've gotten to be fat and ugly and I'm not popular with the worldly crowd.
They don't invite me to their cocktail parties because they know I'm not coming.
And I wouldn't go if they invited me.
And I wouldn't know what to do if I got there.
I'd feel so uncomfortable.
So I'm not popular with the worldly crowd, the society crowd.
And I have arthritis in both my knees.
And I don't get around like I used to.
I don't go to any kind of parties anymore.
And yet, I don't imagine there's anybody in this town that's any happier than I am.
I don't see how they could be.
I'm just warming up air all the time, and I'm so excited about going to heaven.
I'm looking forward to it.
And the other day, I was reading one of Billy Graham's books, Angels.
And I believe it's in that book that he was telling about his mother's mother, his grandmother, was nine, and they had her propped up in bed.
And she said, all of a sudden, she said,
Oh, I see Jesus.
I see heaven.
And she says, and there is Ben.
Ben was her husband who had died before.
And I tell you, I just got so excited because I know my husband's going to be sitting there waiting to welcome me when I go to heaven.
He said a few days before he died, he'd wait for me in heaven.
And not too long ago, God let me see him in heaven in my dream.
And I just really am excited about going to heaven.
It's going to be the greatest day of my life.
The only thing is, I haven't done enough work for the Lord.
I'm not going to have enough gifts to take Him when I go.
And I haven't won enough lost souls to Christ.
So for that reason, I'm happy to stay here until He's ready for me to come.
But as you see, my life has not been spectacular or fabulous according to the world's standards.
And now I think I've told you about everything I know about insane.
So is me too.
